step.context:
\text{The following substitution would convert} \\
I=\int\dfrac{\sqrt{\tan x}}{\sin x \cos x}\, dx \text{ to }
  I=\int\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{t}}\, dt

step.reason:
\dfrac{\sqrt{\tan x}}{\sin x \cos x} 
  =\dfrac{\sqrt{\tan x}}{\tan x\cos^2 x}
  =\dfrac{\sec ^2x}{\sqrt{\tan x}} \\
\tan x=t\implies \sec ^2 x\, dx=dt \\
\therefore \int\dfrac{\sqrt{\tan x}}{\sin x \cos x}\, dx 
  =\int\dfrac{\sec ^2x\, dx}{\sqrt{\tan x}}
  =\int\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{t}}\, dt

step.context:
\text{If }I=\int\dfrac{\sqrt{\tan x}}{\sin x \cos x}\, dx
  =\int\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{t}}\, dt \\
\text{then is the following correct?}
